<font color="#FF0000">WHAT'S IN A NAME?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Mar  3  4:08:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
If a person or group of people kill people, what difference <br>
does it make whether they or someone else calls them a &quot;Communist&quot;. Was the slaughter in Rawanda not as bad because neither side was a &quot;Communist&quot;. Would it have been worse if one side had been? When in Indonesia, one million innocent people were slaughtered, was that not as bad because the victims happened to be Communists? What difference does it make what someone is called? It's just a word. People should be judged on their actions, not on what they are called. If one of the two sides in Rawanda were called &quot;Communist&quot;, would that make them more evil? Gerald seems to think that if someone is called a &quot;Communist&quot;, that makes them evil, and causes them to kill people. In reality, if someone kills someone, they are therefore evil, and it's completely irrelevant whether they are or are not called a <br>
&quot;Communist&quot;. <br><br>
&quot;Local Communists&quot; were no threat to anyone. The American Communist Party was in no way involved in espionage or anything else. If you persecute people for simply being members of the Communist Party, then you really would be similar to the Soviet Union. Nelson Mandela and the ANC had Communist sympathies. Gorbachev and Yeltsin were Communist.<br>
Were they evil?<br><br>
Obviously, the Soviet Union would never have attacked Western Europe, since it would have caused a nuclear war. <br>
Besides, if you look throughout history, the Mongols, Napolean, the Crimean War, the Russo-Japanese War, <br>
World War I, and World War II, these all involve foreigners attacking Russia. Russia does not have a history of attacking other countries. No Soviet leader would have launched nuclear weapons. However, John F. Kennedy came within a hair's breadth of using nuclear weapons during the Cuban Missle Crisis. He made a big deal about Soviet missles in Cuba even though we had U.S. nuclear missles on the Turkish-Soviet border aimed at Moscow. The U.S. flew U2 planes over Soviet territory thousands of times, each of which was an act of war. The Soviet Union never flew a plane over the United States.<br><br>
Romania was ruled by the brutal Communist dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. He was so ruthless that the Soviets shunned him.<br>
The United States was so happy that he was not in lockstep with Moscow, we tried to become his friend. Queen Elizabeth gave him a knighthood. He toured the United States, including Disneyland. He became friends with Shirley Temple.<br>
I guess the Ceausescus were always attracted to the idea of young girls. His son raped a famous Romanian Olympic gymnast with pigtails. The only reason we cozied up to him was because he was breaking with Moscow. In fact he was shunned by Moscow because he was so bloodthirsty, so ruthless, killed so many of his own people, that the Soviets were horrified. We did this even though he was Communist, simply to distance him from the Soviet Union. Nixon opened the door to China even though they were Communist, just to put more distance between them and the Soviet Union. This was referred to as &quot;playing the China card&quot;, as if global politics was a board game played by the American and Soviet leaders. We were focused entirely on this game, on our opponent, and if necessary we would dispense with our use of the word &quot;Communist&quot; as our demonization word. However, when we did use the word to justify our actions we used only to mean &quot;Soviet-allied&quot; which was completely independant of how evil they may or may not be.<br><br>
I'm amazed that in Gerald's post, he says &quot;don't overestimate the ignorance of the average American on Communism&quot; and then puts forward as supposed evidence of this, the fact that Americans were afraid of &quot;Communists&quot; gaining control of the CIO. That's McCarthyism, like saying that &quot;Communists&quot; controlled Hollywood. A previous person to have posted on this board said that people in his home town thought that attempts to fluorinate the water was a <br>
&quot;commie plot&quot;. That's evidence of the profound ignorance and paranoia of the average person. Why would you say that if the point you are trying to make is that they were not ignorant?
